# Task: lay

Make the robot lay down flat. A quadruped lay is characterized by:
- All four legs fold under the body, with feet pulled in toward the center.
- The body is level (roll ≈ 0, pitch ≈ 0).
- Base height is low, close to the physical minimum (~0.10 m).

# Strategy hints

- All four feet should target similar foot_z values; asymmetry in foot_z causes pitch.
- Pulling all feet up (less-negative foot_z) lowers the body uniformly.
- Keep front-rear foot_x symmetric about the body center to avoid pitching. Front foot_x should roughly mirror rear foot_x in magnitude.
- Minimum base height is around 0.10 m — beyond that the legs collide with the body.
- The three reward terms (|Δh|, |Δroll|, |Δpitch|) are additive. All three must be small for high reward.

